The dataset contains 12 columns:

  • PassengerId: Passengers are assigned to a number in the dataset
  • Survived: If the passenger survived (1) or not (0)
  • Pclass: The class of the passenger
  • Name: The name of the passenger
  • Sex: The gender of the passenger
  • Age: The age of the passenger
  • SibSp: The number of siblings/spouses aboard the ship
  • Parch: The number of parents/children aboard the ship
  • Ticket: The ticket number of the pasenger
  • Fare: The ticket price
  • Cabin: The cabin number of the passenger
  • Embarked: Where did the passengers embarked

(More information: https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/data)

Let's get more information about the dataset:

In [4]:
 # Create a Survival variable from the Survived variable
titanic_data['Survival'] = titanic_data.Survived.map({0 : 'Died', 1 : 'Survived'})
# Create a Class variable from the Pclass variable
titanic_data['Class'] = titanic_data.Pclass.map({1 : 'First Class', 2 : 'Second Class', 3 : 'Third Class'})
# Create a Ports variable from the Embarked variable
titanic_data['Ports'] = titanic_data.Embarked.map({'C' : 'Cherbourg', 'Q' : 'Queenstown', 'S' : 'Southampton'})
# Create a Gender variable from the Sex variable
titanic_data['Gender'] = titanic_data.Sex.map({'male' : 'Male', 'female' : 'Female'})
# Create the Family variable by adding the SibSp and Parch variables
titanic_data['Family'] = titanic_data['SibSp'] + titanic_data['Parch']

II - Data Exploration¶

Lot of interesting data here. Let's do some quick analysis and visualization so we can have a better feeling about the data.

First let's create a function to plot quickly the charts and print some information about the variable.

In [5]:
# Function to calculate percentage and value in pie charts (Suggested by my reviewer)
def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        total = sum(values)
        val = int(round(pct*total/100.0))
        return '{p:.2f}%  ({v:d})'.format(p=pct,v=val)
    return my_autopct

# Function to create charts
def plot_chart(variable, kind='pie', bins = 0):
    
    # Takes variables of the dataframe if not inputed
    #if variable_names == {}:
    variable_names = {}
    for index in titanic_data[variable].value_counts().index:
        variable_names[index] = index
        
    # Plot a Pie Chart
    if kind == 'pie':
        
        # Make the charts bigger
        ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 6))
        
        # Retrieves labels from the dataframe
        labels = [variable_names[category] for category in titanic_data[variable].value_counts().index]
        
        # Plot the chart
        titanic_data[variable].value_counts().plot(kind = kind,
                              title = variable + ' variable repartition (in %)',
                              labels = labels, colormap = 'Accent',                       
                              autopct=make_autopct(titanic_data.groupby(variable).size()), fontsize=10)
        plt.show()
        
        # Print some keys statistics
        print(variable + ' variable summary')
        for keys in variable_names.keys():
            value = len(titanic_data[titanic_data[variable] == keys])
            percent = round(100 * value / sum(~titanic_data[variable].isnull()),2)
            print(str(variable_names[keys] + ':\t' + f'{value} passengers ({percent}%).').expandtabs(25))
    
    # Plot an histogram
    if kind == 'hist':
        
        # Plot histogram when bins are not given
        if bins == 0:
            titanic_data[variable].plot(kind = kind,
                              title = variable + ' variable repartition (in %)',                   
                              fontsize=10)
        # Plot histogram when bins are given   
        else:    
            titanic_data[variable].plot(kind = kind,
                              title = variable + ' variable repartition (in %)',                   
                              fontsize=10, bins = bins)
        plt.show()
        
        # Print some keys statistics
        print(variable + ' variable summary')
        median = round(np.median(titanic_data[variable].dropna()), 2)
        mean = round(np.mean(titanic_data[variable].dropna()), 2)
        print(str('Median ' + variable + ':\t' + f'{median}.').expandtabs(25))
        print(str('Mean ' + variable + ':\t' + f'{mean}.').expandtabs(25))

8 - The Name variable¶

Here let's try to do something a bit different and try get the nationality of passengers based on their names.

I decided to use the API provided by NamePrism (http://www.name-prism.com/) since, after some reserch it seems to be the best free and ready to use etchnicity classsifier.

In [14]:
# Define function to return the ethnicity of the person
def find_ethnicity(name):
    
    # Keep maiden name or use 'normal' name
    if '(' in name:
        adjusted_name = name.split('(', 1)[1].split(')')[0]
        adjusted_name
    else:
        adjusted_name = name
    
    # Adjust characters which are not supported by Name Prism API
    adjusted_name = adjusted_name.replace("/", " ")
    adjusted_name = adjusted_name.replace(",", " ")
    titles = ['Mr.', 'Miss.', 'Master.', 'Mrs.', 'Don.', '/']
    for title in titles:   
        adjusted_name = adjusted_name.replace(title, "")
        
    adjusted_name = adjusted_name.replace("  ", " ")
    
    # Create API link 
    API_link = 'http://www.name-prism.com/api/' + adjusted_name.replace(' ', '%20')
    
    # Put the results of the query in a panda dataframe
    results = pd.read_csv(API_link, header = None)
    
    # Return the ethnicity which have the highest percentage and the percentage
    ethnicity = results.loc[results[1].idxmax()][0]
    percentage  = results.loc[results[1].idxmax()][1]
    
    # Return the ethnicity
    return ethnicity, percentage

Now let's run the function and store it in another dataframe.

In [15]:
test_name_data = pd.DataFrame()
test_name_data['Name'] = titanic_data['Name']
test_name_data['Ethnicity'], test_name_data['percentage'] = zip(*titanic_data['Name'].apply(find_ethnicity))

Let's plot the percentage returned with the ethnicity to see how certain we are of the ethnicity of passengers.

In [16]:
test_name_data['percentage'].plot(kind='hist', bins=50, normed=True, cumulative = True)
Out[16]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x274a24a7da0>

We can see that the certainty of the ethnicity of passengers is evenly distributed.

We would have to determine a threshold of certainty for the passenger names.

The threshold should be:

  • high enough to have a high certainty of the passengers ethnicity
  • low enough to have enough passengers data to make relevant analysis

One of the most straightforward way to determine such a threshold would be to have a look at French names and see which names are 'typically' French. We will consider a name 'French' if either the first name or family names is stereotypically French.

Disclaimer: I do not pretend to know all the names used in French but still have a pretty good idea for having live there a few decades.

In [17]:

                                                                                    bins=50, 
                                                                                    normed=True, 
                                                                                    cumulative = True)
Out[17]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x274a215d3c8>
In [18]:
test_name_data[(test_name_data['Ethnicity'] == 'European-French') & (test_name_data['percentage'] > 0.8)][['Name','percentage']].shape
Out[18]:
(41, 2)

Few observations from looking at the french names:

  • Most of them are not French or stereotypically French
  • The threshold will need to be quite high in order for us to have a high certainty of the ethnicity of the passengers

Out of 158 passengers classified as French, only 37 had stereotipical French names. At a 0.8 threshold we will have 41 passengers classified as French, with 33 with stereotipical French names.

Let's see how many passengers would be left in the dataset if we use this confidence threshold.

In [19]:
test_name_data[test_name_data['percentage'] >= 0.8]['Ethnicity'].shape
Out[19]:
(209,)

Unfortunately, with only 209 passengers, we would not be able to have data relevant enough in order to make meaninful analysis.

Let's not forget that 682 passengers were not assigned ethnicity with that confidence threshold, which would dramatically change the results of our analysis if they were assigned.

Therefore, it would be difficult to continue rigourously our analysis on ethnicity/nationality with such results.

It would have been interesting to push the analysis further:

  • We could have try another service provider for ethnicity and add it to our results.
  • We could have labeled the dataset manually rather than with algorithm.

Since name-prism used names of emails and twitter account and assign the name based on the location, It understandably gives unreliable results for several reasons:

  • Internationalization of names
  • Changes in demographics

(name-prism's paper (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1708.07903.pdf))

In [20]:
def count_bar_chart(survived, did_not_survived, ind, x_labels, ymax, top_adjustment):
    
    # Create bars for survivors
    plt.bar(ind, 
            survived,
            width = 0.95,
            color = 'mediumaquamarine')
    
    # Create bars for non-survivors
    plt.bar(ind,
            did_not_survived, 
            bottom = survived, 
            width = 0.95,
            color = 'crimson')
    
    # Loop through bars to write counts
    select_bar = 0
    for bar in np.arange(len(x_labels)):
        plt.text(select_bar, survived[bar]/2.25, "{:}".format(round(survived[bar], 0)), ha='center')
        plt.text(select_bar, (did_not_survived[bar]/2.25+survived[bar]), "{:}".format(round(did_not_survived[bar], 0)), ha='center', color = 'white', weight = 'bold')
        plt.text(select_bar, ((did_not_survived[bar]+survived[bar]+top_adjustment)), "{:}".format(round(did_not_survived[bar]+survived[bar], 0)), ha='center', weight = 'bold')
        select_bar += 1
    
    # Limit the height of the chart    
    plt.ylim(ymax=ymax)

def percent_bar_chart(survived_percent, did_not_survived_percent, ind, x_labels):
    
    # Create bars for survivors
    p1 = plt.bar(ind,
                 survived_percent,
                 width = 0.95,
                 color = 'mediumaquamarine')
    
    # Create bars for non-survivors
    p2 = plt.bar(ind,
                 did_not_survived_percent, 
                 bottom = survived_percent, 
                 width = 0.95,
                 color = 'crimson')
    
    # Loop through bars to write counts
    select_bar = 0
    for bar in np.arange(len(x_labels)):
        plt.text(select_bar, survived_percent[bar]/2.25, "{:.0%}".format(round(survived_percent[bar], 2)), ha='center')
        plt.text(select_bar, (did_not_survived_percent[bar]/2.25+survived_percent[bar]), "{:.0%}".format(round(did_not_survived_percent[bar], 2)), ha='center', color = 'white', weight = 'bold')
        select_bar += 1
In [22]:
def calculate_survavibilty(dataframe, variable, x_labels):
    
    for label in x_labels:
        psurvived = dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] == label) & (dataframe['Survived'] == 1)]['Survived'].value_counts().iloc[0]
        pdid_not_survived = dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] == label) & (dataframe['Survived'] == 0)]['Survived'].value_counts().iloc[0]
        survived.append(psurvived)
        did_not_survived.append(pdid_not_survived)      
        survived_percent.append(psurvived / len(dataframe.loc[dataframe[variable] ==label]))
        did_not_survived_percent.append(pdid_not_survived / len(dataframe.loc[dataframe[variable] ==label]))
        
    return psurvived

def survived_stacked_bar_chart(dataframe, variable, order_list = []):
       
    # Create x_labels if empty
    x_labels = {}
    if order_list == []:
        for value in dataframe[variable].value_counts().index:
            x_labels[value] = value
    else:
        for value in order_list:
            x_labels[value] = value
    
    # Set up relevant variables
    ind = np.arange(len(x_labels))
    labels = x_labels.values()
    
    # Start empty lists
    survived = []
    survived_percent = []
    did_not_survived = []
    did_not_survived_percent = []
    
    # Loop through the labels to select relevant data 
    for label in x_labels:
        try:
            psurvived = dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] == label) & (dataframe['Survived'] == 1)]['Survived'].value_counts().iloc[0]
        except:
            psurvived = 0
        try:
            pdid_not_survived = dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] == label) & (dataframe['Survived'] == 0)]['Survived'].value_counts().iloc[0]
        except:
            pdid_not_survived = 0
        survived.append(psurvived)
        did_not_survived.append(pdid_not_survived)      
        try:
            survived_percent.append(psurvived / len(dataframe.loc[dataframe[variable] ==label]))
        except:
            survived_percent = 0
        try:
            did_not_survived_percent.append(pdid_not_survived / len(dataframe.loc[dataframe[variable] ==label]))
        except:
            did_not_survived_percent = 0
    
    # Set up relevant variables  
    labels = x_labels.values()
    plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 8))
    ymax = 1.115 * max([survived[bar]+did_not_survived[bar] for bar in np.arange(len(x_labels))])
    top_adjustment = 0.035 * max([survived[bar]+did_not_survived[bar] for bar in np.arange(len(x_labels))])
    
    # Create the first chart
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    count_bar_chart(survived, did_not_survived, ind, x_labels, ymax, top_adjustment) 
    
    # Create the legend
    plt.legend((p1[0], p2[0]), 
           (['Survived', 'Did not Survived']), 
           bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), 
           loc=2, 
           borderaxespad=0.)
    
    # Add title to the chart
    plt.title(variable + ' Variable Stacked Bars Chart')
    
    # Remove x & y ticks
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
          
    # Create the second chart
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    percent_bar_chart(survived_percent, did_not_survived_percent, ind, x_labels)
    
    # Add x ticks labels and remove y tikcs
    plt.xticks(ind, (labels), rotation = 45)
    plt.yticks([]) 
    
    # Reduce the space between charts
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

1 - The Pclass & Fare variables and Survability¶

Let's have a look at the relationship between the Pclass & Fare variables and the Survived variable.

First, let's have a look if we can see a relationship between the Pclass variable and the Survived using our newly written custom functions.

In [24]:
survived_stacked_bar_chart(titanic_data, 'Class', ['First Class', 'Second Class', 'Third Class'])

As expected, there is an obvious trend here: the higher the passenger class, the higher the chance of survival.

The chance of survival roughly increase by 20% per passenger class.

let's calculate the Chi-Square to confirm our visual observation.

Null hypothesis: The Pclass variable has no impact on the Survived variable.

Alternative hypothesis: the Pclass variable has an impact on the Survived variable.

p-value level: 0.05.

In [25]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

chi2_contingency([titanic_data[titanic_data['Survived'] == 0].groupby(['Pclass']).count()['Survived'].tolist(),
                 titanic_data[titanic_data['Survived'] == 1].groupby(['Pclass']).count()['Survived'].tolist()])
Out[25]:
(102.88898875696056,
 4.5492517112987927e-23,
 2,
 array([[ 133.09090909,  113.37373737,  302.53535354],
        [  82.90909091,   70.62626263,  188.46464646]]))

the p-value of the chi-square test is way below the p-value threshold, therefore we can reject the null hypothesis: The Pclass variable has an impact on the Survived variable.

This confirm our visual observation: to have the higher chance of survival, better be in First class.

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x274a24547f0>

It is very obvious on the swarmplot that the chance of survival increase with the class.

It seems that in First and Second class, a higher fare might give you a better chance of survival. This does not seems to be the case in third class.

Let's verify the hypothesis with one way ANOVA tests.

First, let's start with the relationship between the Fare and the Survived variable.

null hypothesis: There is no relationship between the Fare and the Survived variable.

alternative hypothesis: There is a relationship between the Fare and the Survived variable.

p-value: 0.05

In [29]:
f_oneway(titanic_data[titanic_data['Survived'] == 0]['Fare'].tolist(),
         titanic_data[titanic_data['Survived'] == 1]['Fare'].tolist())
Out[29]:
F_onewayResult(statistic=63.030764228044482, pvalue=6.1201893419218733e-15)

The p-value is below the 0.05 threshold therefore the one way ANOVA test confirmed our intuition that there is a relationship between the Fare and the Survived variable.

Let's now have a look at the effect of the Fare variable on the Survived variable inside the different classes.

null hypothesis: there is no relationship between the Fare and Survived variable inside a specific class.

alternative hypothesis: there is a relationship between the Fare and Survived variable inside a specific class.

p-value: 0.05

In [30]:
for pclass in [1,2,3]:
    print(str(pclass) + ' class one way ANOVA test:')
    print(f_oneway(titanic_data[(titanic_data['Pclass'] == pclass) & (titanic_data['Survived'] == 0)]['Fare'].tolist(),
                     titanic_data[(titanic_data['Pclass'] == pclass) & (titanic_data['Survived'] == 1)]['Fare'].tolist()))

1 class one way ANOVA test:
F_onewayResult(statistic=8.0995644842355397, pvalue=0.004858011186235532)
2 class one way ANOVA test:
F_onewayResult(statistic=1.7877991334735683, pvalue=0.18286333148735787)
3 class one way ANOVA test:
F_onewayResult(statistic=0.00042250950053052073, pvalue=0.98360899339697849)

Interestlingly, the Fare variable only have an impact on the Survived variable within the first class.

CONCLUSION:

  • The chance of survival greatly increase by class (a 20% jump in chance of surviving per class).
  • The chance of survival increase with higher fares.
  • The chance of survival increase in first class with higher fares.

In [33]:
def filtered_stacked_bar_charts(dataframe, variable, variable_group_by, x_order = [],  c_order = []):
    
    # Create c_labels if empty
    c_labels = {}
    if c_order == []:
        for value in dataframe[variable_group_by].value_counts().index:
            c_labels[value] = value
    else:
        for value in c_order:
            c_labels[value] = value
    
    # Create x_labels if empty
    x_labels ={}
    if x_order == []:
        for value in dataframe[variable].value_counts().index:
            x_labels[value] = value
    else:
        for value in x_order:
            x_labels[value] = value

    # Set up relevant variables
    num_subplots = len(c_labels) 
    plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 8))
    
    # Loop through variables to create charts
    for chart, c_label in zip(np.arange(num_subplots), c_labels):
        survived = []
        survived_percent = []
        did_not_survived = []
        did_not_survived_percent = []
        
        # Loop through the labels to select relevant data 
        for label in x_labels:

            try:
                psurvived = dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] == label) & (dataframe['Survived'] == 1) & (dataframe[variable_group_by] == c_label)]['Survived'].value_counts().iloc[0]
            except:
                psurvived = 0
                
            try:
                pdid_not_survived = dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] == label) & (dataframe['Survived'] == 0)& (dataframe[variable_group_by] == c_label)]['Survived'].value_counts().iloc[0]
            except:
                pdid_not_survived = 0
                
                
            survived.append(psurvived)
            did_not_survived.append(pdid_not_survived)    
            
            try:
                survived_percent.append(psurvived / len(dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] ==label) & (dataframe[variable_group_by] == c_label)]))
            except:
                survived_percent = 0
            try:    
                did_not_survived_percent.append(pdid_not_survived / len(dataframe.loc[(dataframe[variable] ==label) & ((dataframe[variable_group_by] == c_label))]))
            except:
                did_not_survived_percent = 0
        
        # Set up relevant variables
        ind = np.arange(len(x_labels))  
        ymax = 1.115*max([sum(titanic_data.loc[(titanic_data[variable] == x_label) & 
                                               (titanic_data[variable_group_by] == c_label)]['Survived'].value_counts()) 
                          for x_label in x_labels 
                          for c_label in c_labels])
        top_adjustment = ymax / 25
        
        # Create the first chart
        plt.subplot(2,num_subplots,chart +1)
        count_bar_chart(survived, did_not_survived, ind, x_labels, ymax, top_adjustment)
        
        # Add title to the chart
        plt.title(variable + " Variable by " + str(c_labels[c_label]))
        
        # Remove x & y ticks
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        
        # Create the second chart
        plt.subplot(2,num_subplots,chart +1 + num_subplots)
        percent_bar_chart(survived_percent, did_not_survived_percent, ind, x_labels)
        
        # Add x ticks labels and remove y tikcs
        plt.xticks(ind, (label for label in x_labels.values()), rotation = 45)
        plt.yticks([])    
        
        # Reduce the space between charts
        plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend((p1[0], p2[0]), 
           (['Survived', 'Did not Survived']), 
           bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), 
           loc=2, 
           borderaxespad=0.)
In [34]:
filtered_stacked_bar_charts(titanic_data, 
                            'Gender', 
                            'Class',
                             c_order = ['First Class', 'Second Class', 'Third Class'])

Very interesting differences between gender chances of survival.

Female travelling in Third class had a better chance of surviving than male travelling in First class.

Maybe even more interesting is the fact that women travelling in second class had almost had twice more chance of surviving than women in third class.

We do not observe the same bump for male between third and second class but between men in first and second class. Men in first class had more twice more chance of surviving than men in second class.

CONCLUSION:

  • The chance of survival is greater for female.
  • Female in third class had higher chance of survival than male in any class.
  • Female in first and second class had their chance of survival almost multiply by 2 compared to female in third class.
  • Male in first class had their chance of survival multiply by to compared to male in second and third class.

survived_stacked_bar_chart(titanic_data, 'Family', [0, 1, 2, 3])

The trend here is very interesting, we can see that passengers travelling alone had lower chance of survival and passengers with 3 family members aboard had higher chance of survival.

Could it be explained by other factors?

Let's have a look at the Pclass variable first.

In [48]:
filtered_stacked_bar_charts(titanic_data, 
                            'Family', 
                            'Class',
                            c_order = ["First Class", "Second Class", "Third Class"],
                            x_order = [0, 1, 2, 3])

We do observe a similar trend when looking through the Pclass variable.

Let's now have a look at the Sex variable.

In [49]:
filtered_stacked_bar_charts(titanic_data, 
                            'Family', 
                            'Gender',
                            x_order = [0, 1, 2, 3])

There were around 3 times more men travelling without family than women travelling without family. There were around the same amount of men and women travelling with one or two family members. There were around 2 times more women travelling with 3 family members than men.

This can definitely explain the trend we were seing earlier.

To conclude, it seems that having family on board did not really have influence on the chance of survival.

II - Conclusion¶

Conclusion:

  • The chance of survival greatly increase by class (a 20% jump in chance of surviving per class).
  • The chance of survival increase with higher fares.
  • The chance of survival increase in first class with higher fares but not in other classes (ie. having higher fare in first class increase your chance of surviving compared to other first class passengers).
  • The chance of survival is greater for female.
  • Female in third class had higher chance of survival than male in any class.
  • Female in first and second class had their chance of survival almost multiply by 2 compared to female in third class.
  • Male in first class had their chance of survival multiply by to compared to male in second and third class.
  • Port of embarkation is mostly irrelvant.
  • Male passengers under 15 had greater chance to survival than male over 15 but still less than women.
  • Surprisingly female passengers under 15 had a lower chance of survival than female over 15.
  • Having family onboard is mostly irrelevant.

Best case scenario:

  • First Class
  • Higher Fare
  • Female Chance of survival: 94.11%

Worst Case scenario:

  • Third Class
  • Male
  • Over 15 Chance of survival: 12.83%

Final remarks:

  • The titanic dataset only represent a fraction of the titanic passengers and we cannot know if we can generalize it to the entire passengers population.
  • It would have been interesting to have a complete cabin variable to make an interesting representation to see if cabin distance had an impact on chance of survival.
